The White House has announced that 48 additional public health, medical, and nursing schools from 15 countries have committed to training their students to address the health impacts of climate change. This brings the total number of schools committing to 118 around the world. The commitment aims to ensure that the next generation of health professionals are prepared to effectively address the health impacts of climate change. The Columbia University Mailman School of Public Health will also be creating a Global Consortium on Climate and Health Education to carry forward the commitment and foster global academic partnerships. The announcement highlights the need for global action on climate change and the growing recognition among health professionals of the impact of climate change on people's health. The commitment includes schools from countries such as Australia, Canada, China, France, India, Mexico, Singapore, South Africa, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom.